# Plan: Themes Module

**Date:** 2026-03-04
**Directory:** `plans/20260304-1315-themes-module/`

---

## Summary

Create a dedicated `Theme` model for managing visual themes. Admin creates multiple themes but only ONE can be active at any time. Activating a theme deactivates all others in a transaction. A public endpoint exposes the active theme so the frontend can apply CSS variables, logo, favicon, and custom CSS globally.

This differs from the existing `settings` KV branding approach -- themes are first-class entities with CRUD, preview, and instant switching.

---

## Phases

| # | Phase | Status | File |
|---|-------|--------|------|
| 1 | Database Schema | Pending | [phase-01-database-schema.md](./phase-01-database-schema.md) |
| 2 | Backend API | Pending | [phase-02-backend-api.md](./phase-02-backend-api.md) |
| 3 | Admin UI | Pending | [phase-03-frontend-admin-ui.md](./phase-03-frontend-admin-ui.md) |
| 4 | Theme Application | Pending | [phase-04-theme-application.md](./phase-04-theme-application.md) |

---

## Key Decisions

- **Dedicated table** (`themes`), not `settings` KV -- structured, type-safe, supports multiple themes
- **Single-active constraint** enforced via Prisma `$transaction`: set all to `inactive`, then set target to `active`
- **Public GET** `/themes/active` (no auth) -- consumed by ThemeProvider on every page load
- **Admin CRUD** guarded by `SupabaseAuthGuard` + admin role check
- **CSS variable injection** via a `ThemeProvider` component wrapping the app in `Providers`
- **Default theme** seeded in migration with system defaults (matches current `globals.css` colors)
- **Color format**: hex strings (e.g. `#3b82f6`) -- compatible with CSS variables and HTML color pickers
- **Logo/favicon**: URL strings (same pattern as branding settings, uploaded via Supabase Storage separately)

---

